assessment_details.task_description:
The personal Research Journal is intended to capture your learning through undertaking the course. The journal is both a reflective document of your skills growth as well as a record of your ability to understand and apply key theories and analytical frameworks to organisational innnovation problems.

During the relevant weeks you will be asked to make a submission to the research journal with a reflection on or application of relevant theories and frameworks covered in those weeks. In total, there will be 6 submissions, each worth 10 marks for a total of 60 marks. Note that week 13 is the multi-use week.

See blackboard for details of the assessment and submission dates and times.

that have delivered the greatest impact to you. Previous journal submissions for this subject have included mind-mapping schematics with analyses, audio & video records of evolutionary thinking, animations built to show core conceptual developments throughout the semester as case study attributes emerged and photo essays with audio tracks outlining conceptual innovation highlights.

While there is no set format or word count for the Research Journal , it should capture your personal learning and the key frameworks that have impacted your entrepreneurial thinking in building innovation capabilities, their application in building organizational identity through innovation strategy, portfolio management, stage-gate development processess and innovation culture. You may also choose to include any of the following components:

weekly diary entries that record events or insights that furthered your understanding of innovation, beyond the focal case study;

new ways in which you interpreted key theoretical frameworks as these arose and were tested against the focal case;

a set of diagnostic questions derived from applying the engaged scholarship methodology that you have explored with the focal case and how you could use these in future applications;

Please feel free to mention additional personal observations, such as:

specific people, events and/or experiences which may have contributed to changes in your understanding, and why;

ways in which your understanding and/or sense of engaging with the foundations of innovation capability DID NOT change, and why;

any difficulties you encountered with your academic work this semester, and what, if anything, you did to try to overcome them;

any successes you encountered with your academic work this semester, and what, if anything, you did to incorporate them into your scholarly practice;

multimedia elements that capture your personal journey, such as audio/video podcasts, thought blogs or links to content that impacts your skills development.
